collation.signatures: Quire numbers in Arabic numerals in dry-point, except in quires ending with a parchment leaf.

binding.p: Paste-downs are made up of fragments from at least two manuscripts. One is an ordinal (12th/13th century) covering one fourth of the and half of the . The text on the is from the Common of confessors and virgins, that on the is probably the end of the feast of Catherine and the beginning of the Common of apostles. The other two fragments cover three fourths of the and half of the . The texts are un-identified but both may be from the same manuscript. The text on the left cover is a list of various terms, e.g. annosus, amor, hospes, barba, all with explanations in hexameter(?).

decoNote.p: 3-line blind tooling. Double frames at top and bottom, single frame on sides. Two rectangular panels in the centre square separated by a gutter, also blind tooled: a foliaged staff () and birds (). The panels are blind stamped with circles arranged in corresponding pairs. The motifs, same on both front and back, from top to bottom, left to right are: lion - falconer, pelican - lion with cub, rose - rose, lion with cub - pelican, stag - lion.

binding.condition: Leather worn. Leather straps and clasps missing.

origin.p:
Sweden Uppsala 1485. Finished 24 July and written by Laurentius Gregorii according to the colophon on , see Hedlund (1977)
. The liturgical content in the calendar supports an origin from Uppsala, see Helander (2001)
, and Moberg (1947)
.

provenance.p: The manuscript belonged to the Antiquities archive. The signum 230, written in brown ink in the centre of the , is found in Peringskiöld's inventory from the 1720s, U 90:2, f. 14r, (corrected from 229) with the title: Laurentii Gregorii Liber precum def.. The current signum is established in Helin's catalogue from the 1720s, U 91:2:2.

acquisition.p: From the Antiquities Archive to the Royal Library in 1780.

note.p: This calendar is almost identical to the one in Breviarium Upsalense (printed 1496). Feasts in A 50 but not in Breviarium 1496 are: St Alban, the Seven sleepers and the Octave of St Michael; 27 March is marked as Resurrection day. Feasts in Breviarium Upsalense 1496 not in A 50 are: St Ansgar, St Thomas of Aquino, Compassion of Virgin Mary (6 May), Division of Apostles, St Katarina of Sweden, St Brynolf, St Helen of Constantinople and the Octave of All saints. Bottom of each page in black ink by a contemporary hand: the number of hours for the day and night for each month. Some feasts may be later additions, e.g. Sts Cornelius and Cyprianus added on 15 September and St Nicomedes on 16 september although the dates should be reversed.

msItem.finalRubric: Explicit de tempore. Sequitur aliud Et primo de dedicacione.

note.p: The temporale begins with the first Sunday of Advent and ends with the Twenty-fifth Sunday after Trinity. Two larger rubrics denote subsections:
: rubric in red: Sequitur vigilia sancte trinitatis Ad vesperas super omnia laudate Antiphone;
: underlined in red: Incipiunt capitula et ewangelia Dominicalia cum suis omeliis Dominica 2a post trinitatis Capitulum.
